# Onboarding — one-time setup for {{ project_name }}

Most of this project is green and hardened the moment it is generated. A few controls live in
**GitHub repo settings** rather than in files — by design, so an AI agent working in the repo
cannot edit them away (see [`docs/decisions/0004-agent-resistant-guardrails.md`](docs/decisions/0004-agent-resistant-guardrails.md)).
This is the short list of switches **you** flip once.

## 1. Push the repo to GitHub

```bash
gh repo create {{ github_owner }}/{{ github_repo }} --private --source . --push
```

## 2. Apply the branch ruleset (required)

Makes passing CI + code-owner review a *repo setting*, not a file an agent can rewrite:

```bash
gh auth login                 # needs 'repo' scope + admin on this repo
./scripts/bootstrap-repo.sh   # applies .github/rulesets/main.json (idempotent)
```

After the first PR runs CI once, the `ci-complete` check registers and becomes required. From then
on: no merge without green CI, and any change to the guardrails (CI, security rules, dependency
manifests, spine decision lists — see `.github/CODEOWNERS`) needs a human approval.

> **Solo owner, one identity:** GitHub won't let you approve your own PR. For guardrail changes
> you'll need a second reviewer, or a deliberate admin merge. Feature PRs are unaffected.

**Prove it fails closed (do this once).** The baseline requires *0* approvals, so feature PRs merge
without review — but a change to a code-owned guardrail must require your approval. Verify:

```bash
# On a throwaway branch, edit a guarded file and open a PR:
git switch -c verify-guard && echo "# test" >> .github/workflows/ci.yml
git commit -am "test: guard-review enforcement" && gh pr create -f
gh pr view --json reviewDecision   # expect: REVIEW_REQUIRED (blocked until a code owner approves)
```

If that PR is *not* blocked, code-owner enforcement isn't active — fix it before trusting the repo.
(Phase E2 adds a CI-level meta-guard as a second line of defence.)

## Coming with later hardening phases

These are wired in the template as they land; each is one install/toggle here (kept fail-closed):

- **OSSF Scorecard** — scheduled posture check; may need a read-only PAT for the branch-protection check.
- **Socket.dev** — install the GitHub App on your org and set it to **block** (behavioral supply-chain analysis).
- **cosign + provenance** — enable a container registry (GHCR) and OIDC so CI can sign the image and deploy can verify it.
